%3B%20and%20it%20gets%20to%20the%20root%20of%20why%20your%20child%20is%20asking%20in%20the%20first%20place.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWith%20%26quot%3BAre%20we%20rich%3F%26quot%3B%20in%20particular%2C%20Lieber%20writes%20that%20the%20question%20can%20lead%20to%20discussions%20on%20possessions%2C%20wealth%2C%20and%20what%20it%20actually%20means%20to%20be%20%26quot%3Brich.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EHe%20recommends%20asking%20open-ended%20questions%20to%20steer%20the%20conversation%20to%20the%20conclusion%20that%20we%20don't%20know%20much%20about%20our%20neighbors'%20money%20and%20that%20being%20rich%20isn't%20as%20important%20as%20having%20other%20qualities%2C%20like%20kindness%20and%20creativity.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EOr%2C%20you%20can%20leave%20the%20more%20in-depth%20conversation%20for%20later.%20One%20mom%20and%20sociology%20professor%20whose%20story%20is%20recounted%20in%20%26quot%3BThe%20Opposite%20of%20Spoiled%26quot%3B%20took%20a%20straightforward%20approach%20when%20her%20third-grade%20son%20asked%20if%20his%20family%20was%20rich.%20%26quot%3BIt%20was%20one%20of%20the%20hardest%20things%20I've%20ever%20had%20to%20do%20as%20a%20parent%2C%20but%20I%20looked%20him%20in%20the%20eye%20and%20said%20'yes%2C'%26quot%3B%20she%20told%20Lieber.%20%26quot%3BAnd%20that%20was%20the%20end%20of%20it.%20You're%20supposed%20to%20wait%20for%20them%20to%20follow%20up%20and%20get%20into%20it%2C%20but%20that%20was%20it.%20He%20wanted%20to%20know%2C%20and%20I%20told%20him%20the%20truth.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BSticking%20to%20the%20truth%20is%20good%20when%20it%20comes%20to%20money%2C%20but%20so%20is%20adapting%20your%20message%20to%20your%20kid's%20level%2C%26quot%3B%C2%A0Beth%20Kobliner%20writes%20in%20her%20own%20book%2C%20%26quot%3B%3Cspan%3EMake%20Your%20Kid%20a%20Money%20Genius%20(Even%20If%20You're%20Not)%3A%20A%20Parents'%20Guide%20For%20Kids%203%20to%2023%3C%2Fspan%3E.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EShe%20continued%20in%20a%202017%20interview%20with%20Business%20Insider%3A%20